Part B: Real-World Case Study

Cyber Attack Case Study
WannaCry Ransomware Attack

What Happened?
WannaCry was a ransomware attack that occurred in May 2017.
It spread rapidly across the world by exploiting a vulnerability in Microsoft Windows systems.
Once a computer was infected, the ransomware encrypted files and demanded a ransom payment in Bitcoin to restore access. 
The attack affected more than 200,000 computers across over 150 countries, including hospitals, businesses, and government organizations.

Which Part of the CIA Triad Was Affected?
Availability was the most affected component of the CIA Triad because users were unable to access their files and systems after they were encrypted.
Integrity was also affected because the ransomware modified and encrypted data without authorization.

What Was the Impact?
* Thousands of organizations experienced operational disruptions.
* Hospitals had to cancel appointments and delay treatments.
* Businesses suffered financial losses due to downtime.
* Important files became inaccessible to users.
* Recovery efforts required significant time and resources.

How Could It Have Been Prevented?
* Regularly updating operating systems and software.
* Applying security patches provided by Microsoft.
* Using reliable antivirus and endpoint protection solutions.
* Maintaining regular backups of important data.
* Training users to recognize suspicious emails and attachments.
* Implementing strong network security controls.
